<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangzhou Revokes License of Overseas Firms Over Contracts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guangzhou Revokes License of Overseas Firms Over Contracts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904141894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1402 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1904141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, April 19 (XINHUA) -- The Guangzhou 
authorities in south China's Guangdong Province have revoked the 
licences of 113 overseas-funded enterprises because they refused 
to honor their contracts with the Chinese side. 
  They make up two percent of all the overseas-funded 
enterprises in the city, said the city's Industry and Commerce 
Bureau (ICB) and Foreign Economic and Trade Commission (FETC). 
  The closed enterprises had failed to observe the contracts 
to 
put enough or any capital into their ventures in the city after 
they obtained business licences, the officials said. 
  Some had even suspended operations for long periods for lack 
of funds, and others did not fade out of the enterprises after 
the terms of joint operation with local businesses were ended, 
they said. 
  However, "most of the overseas investors in the city have 
been following national and local laws and regulations and made 
considerable contributions to the city's economic development," 
and "their legal rights and interests have also been protected 
by the governments at all levels," the Guangzhou ICB and FETC 
said. 
  The closed enterprises include: the Guangzhou Flower Garden 
Exhibition Center, the Guangzhou Kangbao Beverage Co. Ltd, and 
Nanguo Hotel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

